10 woman, the health of the woman or her unborn child in serious jeopardy; (ii) serious impairment
11 to bodily functions; or (iii) serious dysfunction of any bodily organ or part. With respect to a
12 pregnant woman who is having contractions that: (A) there is inadequate time to effect a safe
13 transfer to another hospital before delivery; (B) transfer may pose a threat to the health or safety
14 of the woman or the unborn child; or (C) an urgent, unexpected and usually dangerous situation
15 that poses an immediate risk to health, life, property or environment and requires immediate
16 action.
17 “Emergency medical services”, the pre-hospital assessment and treatment and other
18 services utilized in responding to an emergency or provided during the transport of patients to
19 appropriate health care facilities as defined in regulations promulgated by the department.
20 “EMS”, emergency medical services.
21 “Emergency medical service providers”, licensed emergency medical service
22 organizations, including municipal fire departments and private ambulance services, delivering
23 pre-hospital care.
24 “Non-emergent medical condition”, a medical issue identified by emergency medical
25 service providers that does not require immediate treatment at an emergency department to
26 stabilize the patient.
27 “Program”, the emergency medical services treat-in-place pilot program established in
28 this act.
