50 (g) Emergency medical service providers participating in the program shall receive
51 financial incentives to implement and evaluate treat-in-place services effectively.
52 (h) Emergency medical service providers participating in the program shall collect data
53 on patient outcomes, cost savings, patient satisfaction and other metrics as determined by the
54 department for the annual report pursuant to subsection (k).
55 (i) The department shall engage with EMS organizations, health systems, health insurers
56 and patient advocacy groups to ensure the program addresses the needs of patients, providers and
57 communities in the commonwealth.
58 (j) Subject to appropriation, the department shall allocate funding necessary to support
59 the implementation and evaluation of the program.
60 (k) The department shall prepare an annual report that shall include: (i) an evaluation of
61 the program’s effectiveness in improving access to EMS care; (ii) analysis of cost savings and
62 financial sustainability; (iii) collected data by emergency medical service providers pursuant to
63 subsection (h); and (iv) any recommendations for expansion of the treat-in-place model or the
64 program. The annual report shall be submitted, not later than December 31 of each year, to the
65 governor, the chairs of the joint committee on public health, the chairs of the joint committee on
66 health care financing and the clerks of the house of representatives and senate.
